Cleaning Data

Since our dependent variable are “reviews.numHelpful” & “reviews.doRecommend”, we cannot replace the missing values in the column by median or mean. Instead, we will omit any NA’s present

#Remove missing value for 'reviews.numHelpful'
amazon.df <- amazon.df[!is.na(amazon.df$reviews.numHelpful),]
amazon.df$reviews.numHelpful <- ifelse(amazon.df$reviews.numHelpful > 0, 1, 0)
# The proportion of 'Reviews.numHelpful' with all missing values
missing.term<-group_by(amazon.df, amazon.df$reviews.numHelpful)
missing.term<-summarise(missing.term,count=n())
missing.term$count<-as.numeric(missing.term$count)
missing.term<-mutate(missing.term, percent=count/sum(count))
missing.term%>%kable(caption="Table: The proportion of helpful and non-helpful reviews with all missing observations")%>%kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped")

The proportion of “helpful” and “non-helpful” in “reviews.Helpful” in the dataset including all missing values are 9.76% and 90.23% respectively. After removing all missing value, its proportion is 9.6% for “helpful” and 90.39% for “non-helpful” and the dimension of the dataset is 24,574 observations which is large enough to build a predictive model. Therefore, we can remove all missing values without affecting results.

Creating training and validation set with oversampling

helpful <- amazon.df2[amazon.df2$isHelpful == "1",]
none.helpful <- amazon.df2[amazon.df2$isHelpful == "0",]

# partitioning data
set.seed(2)

# create a variable with values of helpful reviews for training data 
train.df.helpful <- helpful[sample(nrow(helpful), 1181),] # 1181 is a half of the total observations of the helpful group

# create a variable with values of non-helpful reviews for training data 
train.df.none.helpful <- none.helpful[sample(nrow(none.helpful), 1181),]

# Combining two groups into one training dataset
train.df <- rbind(train.df.helpful, train.df.none.helpful)
# create a variable with values of helpful reviews for validation data
valid.df.helpful <- helpful[sample(nrow(helpful), 1181),]  

# create a variable with values of non-helpful reviews for validation data 
valid.df.none.helpful <- none.helpful[sample(nrow(none.helpful), 11121),]

# Combining two groups into one validation dataset
valid.df <- rbind(valid.df.helpful, valid.df.none.helpful)
# Checking again
train.checking<-group_by(train.df, reviews.numHelpful)
train.checking<-summarise(train.checking, count=n())
valid.checking<-group_by(valid.df, reviews.numHelpful)
valid.checking<-summarise(valid.checking, count=n())
valid.checking<-mutate(valid.checking, percent=count/sum(count))
train.checking%>%kable(caption="Table: Checking training set after oversampling")%>%kableExtra::kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped")

Evaluating model on validation dataset

MODEL 1: Using balanced dataset

# Using training data to predict the probability in validation dataset
mod1.pred<-predict(mod1, valid.df, type = "response")
# Using cutoff figure to select the best cutoff value
accT = c()
for (cut in seq(0,1,0.1)){
  cm <- confusionMatrix(factor(ifelse(mod1.pred> cut,1,0)), factor(valid.df$isHelpful))
  accT = c(accT, cm$overall[1])
}

Decile Chart

decile.data<-data.frame("actual" = valid.df$isHelpful, "probability" = mod1.pred)
gain.mod1<-gains(decile.data$actual, decile.data$probability)
midpoints.mod1 <-barplot(gain.mod1$mean.resp/mean(decile.data$actual), names.arg= gain.mod1$depth, ylim = c(0,6),
xlab = "Percentile", ylab = "Mean Response Yes", main = "Figure: Decile-wise lift chart")
text(midpoints.mod1, gain.mod1$mean.resp/mean(decile.data$actual)+0.5, labels=round(gain.mod1$mean.resp/mean(decile.data$actual), 1), cex = 1)
